<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/67528820-priscilla-king"><img alt="" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_100x100-259587f1619f5253426a4fa6fb508831.png" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/67528820-priscilla-king">Priscilla King</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">Well...the slave characters are caricatures, but so are all the other characters. The main ex-slave character, Cassie, is your basic Black Matriarch A<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">Well...the slave characters are caricatures, but so are all the other characters. The main ex-slave character, Cassie, is your basic Black Matriarch As Seen By Small Scared White Boy. If you define racist as promoting hate or contempt for a "race" of people, I don't think it's racist at all. I think Gurganus, being a satirist, shows a certain amount of contempt for humans in general. Since this book reminds me of nothing at all about either Maddow or Turner Diaries, if they're at the ends of a scale of 1 to 10 I'd give "Widow" a 5.<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
