<div id="review_126066306" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/126066306" />
    <a title="Alicia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1730194-alicia"><img alt="Alicia" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1230665575p2/1730194.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/126066306?book_show_action=true">Oct 13, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Alicia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Alicia" href="/user/show/1730194-alicia">Alicia</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer126066306" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1537497765822168471">I probably shouldn&apos;t say I read this book because I only read 50 of the 700 pages. I did watch the movie, though. Does that count?<br/><br/>The narrator, Lucille (Lucy) Marsden, tells the story of her marriage to &quot;Captain&quot; Will Marsden, the Civil War&apos;s last survivor, whom she married when she was 15 and he was 51!! She also tells about her husband&apos;s experiences in the war, the burning of her mother-in-law&apos;s plantation by Sherman&apos;s men, and the abduction from Africa of a former Marsden slave, midwife to Lu</span>
  <span id="freeText1537497765822168471" style="display:none">I probably shouldn't say I read this book because I only read 50 of the 700 pages. I did watch the movie, though. Does that count?<br /><br />The narrator, Lucille (Lucy) Marsden, tells the story of her marriage to "Captain" Will Marsden, the Civil War's last survivor, whom she married when she was 15 and he was 51!! She also tells about her husband's experiences in the war, the burning of her mother-in-law's plantation by Sherman's men, and the abduction from Africa of a former Marsden slave, midwife to Lucy's nine children as well as her best friend. <br /><br />I expected this book to be about the Civil War but most of it was actually about their every day life. It was a little too much information sometimes. She literally 'tells all'! I found it fascinating (but embarrassing) to see how people lived not even 100 years ago. So different!<br /><br />Lucy was extremely verbose. The author could have probably cut the novel in half and still kept all the content. It was so drawn out that I just couldn't go on. Maybe I'll actually read it at a later date when I don't feel rushed. I do enjoy literature about that time period in our country's history. </span>
  <a data-text-id="1537497765822168471" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


